{"parse":{"title":"Bliss point (food)","pageid":46294636,"revid":837497273,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In the formulation of <a href=\"/wiki/Convenience_food\" title=\"Convenience food\">food products</a>, the <b>bliss point</b> is the amount of an ingredient such as <a href=\"/wiki/Salt\" title=\"Salt\">salt</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Sugar\" title=\"Sugar\">sugar</a>, or <a href=\"/wiki/Fat\" title=\"Fat\">fat</a> which optimizes <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tastiness&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Tastiness (page does not exist)\">tastiness</a>. Pioneering work on the bliss point was carried out by American <a href=\"/wiki/Market_research\" title=\"Market research\">market researcher</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Psychophysics\" title=\"Psychophysics\">psychophysicist</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Howard_Moskowitz\" title=\"Howard Moskowitz\">Howard Moskowitz</a>, known for his successful work in product creation and optimization for foods ranging from spaghetti sauce to <a href=\"/wiki/Soft_drink\" title=\"Soft drink\">soft drinks</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYTMag022013_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYTMag022013-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Moskowitz describes the bliss point as \"that sensory profile where you like food the most.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The bliss point for salt, sugar, or fat is a range within which perception is that there is neither too much nor too little, but the \"just right\" amount of saltiness, sweetness, or richness. The human body has evolved to favor foods delivering these tastes: the brain responds with a \"reward\" in the form of a jolt of <a href=\"/wiki/Endorphin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Endorphin\">endorphins</a>, remembers what we did to get that reward, and makes us want to do it again, an effect run by <a href=\"/wiki/Dopamine\" title=\"Dopamine\">dopamine</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Neurotransmitter\" title=\"Neurotransmitter\">neurotransmitter</a>. Combinations of sugar, fat, and salt act <a href=\"/wiki/Synergistic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Synergistic\">synergistically</a>, and are more rewarding than any one alone. In food product optimization, the goal is to include two or three of these nutrients at their bliss point.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bliss_point_(food)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Hyperreality\" title=\"Hyperreality\">Hyperreality</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Food_industry\" title=\"Food industry\">food industry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Beverage_industry\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Beverage industry\">beverage industry</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bliss_point_(food)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-NYTMag022013-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-NYTMag022013_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Michael Moss (February 20, 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/24/magazine/the-extraordinary-science-of-junk-food.html?pagewanted=all\">\"The Extraordinary Science of Addictive Junk Food\"</a>. <i>The New York Times Magazine</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">March 1,</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times+Magazine&amp;rft.atitle=The+Extraordinary+Science+of+Addictive+Junk+Food&amp;rft.date=2013-02-20&amp;rft.au=Michael+Moss&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2013%2F02%2F24%2Fmagazine%2Fthe-extraordinary-science-of-junk-food.html%3Fpagewanted%3Dall&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABliss+point+%28food%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Wildt, Grace. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.retroreport.org/voices/the-bliss-point/\">\"The Bliss Point\"</a>. <i>Retro Report</i>. Retro Report<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">6 January</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Retro+Report&amp;rft.atitle=The+Bliss+Point&amp;rft.aulast=Wildt&amp;rft.aufirst=Grace&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.retroreport.org%2Fvoices%2Fthe-bliss-point%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABliss+point+%28food%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fcourses.bio.indiana.edu%2FL104-Bonner%2FF12%2FimagesF12%2FL8%2FBlissPoint.html&amp;date=2015-04-03\">\"Biology of Food: The Bliss Point\"</a>. Indiana University (Department of Biology). Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href